  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001_8",
    "text": "A–2 We show more precisely that the game terminates with one player holding all of the pennies if and only if n = 2m + 1 or n = 2m + 2 for some m. First suppose we are in the following situation for some k ≥ 2. (Note: for us, a \"move\" consists of two turns, starting with a one-penny pass.)",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.09411764705882353,
      0.5527272727272727,
      0.49019607843137253,
      0.64
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001",
    "order": 15
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001_18",
    "text": "",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5576470588235294,
      0.5933333333333334,
      0.7780392156862745,
      0.6103030303030303
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001",
    "order": 16
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001_19",
    "text": "A-5 We may discard any solutions for which a1 ≠ a2, since those come in pairs; so assume a1 = a2. Similarly, we may assume that a3 = a4, a5 = a6, a7 = a8, a9 = a10. Thus we get the equation",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5231372549019608,
      0.6181818181818182,
      0.9192156862745098,
      0.676969696969697
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001",
    "order": 17
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001_9",
    "text": "– Except for the player to move, each player has k pennies; – The player to move has at least k pennies.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.14666666666666667,
      0.649090909090909,
      0.49019607843137253,
      0.6987878787878787
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001",
    "order": 18
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001_10",
    "text": "We claim then that the game terminates if and only if the number of players is a power of 2. First suppose the number of players is even; then after m complete rounds, every other player, starting with the player who moved first, will have m more pennies than initially, and the others will all have 0. Thus we are reduced to the situation with half as many players; by this process, we eventually reduce to the case where the number of play- ers is odd. However, if there is more than one player, after two complete rounds everyone has as many pen- nies as they did before (here we need m ≥ 2), so the game fails to terminate. This verifies the claim.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12705882352941175,
      0.7078787878787879,
      0.49019607843137253,
      0.8818181818181818
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001",
    "order": 19
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001_20",
    "text": "Again, we may assume a1 = a3 and a5 = a7, so we get 4/a1 + 4/a5 + 2/a9 = 1; and a1 = a5, so 8/a1 +2/a9 = 1. This implies that (a1 − 8)(a9 − 2) = 16, which by counting has 5 solutions. Thus N1o is odd.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.556078431372549,
      0.7169696969696969,
      0.92,
      0.7745454545454545
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001",
    "order": 20
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001_21",
    "text": "A–6 Clearly xn+1 is a polynomial in c of degree n, so it suf- fi ces to identify n values of c for which xn+1 = 0. We claim these are c = n − 1 − 2r for r = 0, 1, . . .,n − 1; in this case, xk is the coefficient of −1 in the polyno- mial f (t) = (1 − t)(1 + t)n−1−r. This can be verified by noticing that f satisfi es the differential equation",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5231372549019608,
      0.7836363636363637,
      0.92,
      0.8715151515151515
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001",
    "order": 21
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_001_11",
    "text": "Returning to the original game, note that after one com- plete round, [\"2」 players remain, each with 2 pennies except for the player to move, who has either 3 or 4 pen- nies. Thus by the above argument, the game terminates if and only if [n is a power of 2, that is, if and only if n = 2m + 1 or n = 2m + 2 for some m.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
